'Fes' or 'Fez' (, Moroccan Arabic , Berber: Fas, ⴼⴰⵙ) is the third largest city
of Morocco, with a population of approximately 1 million (2010). It is the
capital of the Fès-Boulemane region.

'Fas el Bali' is a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Its medina, the larger of the two
medinas of Fes, is believed to be the world's largest contiguous car-free urban
area. Al-Qarawiyyin, founded in AD 859, is the oldest continuously functioning
madrasa in the world. The city has been called the "Mecca of the West" and the
"Athens of Africa".<ref>[http://riad-hp.com/maroc/istor/ History of Fes]</ref>
